@hp_1__ no, wait. In science the word theory doesn't refer to something that hasn't been proven. The word theory is something that describes WHY something happens (big bang theory explaining why of the expansion, relativity theory explaining why gravity), as opposed to LAW which is something that describes HOW something happens (Newton's gravitational law only described how gravity happens under some limitations, not why there is gravity). So in science the world THEORY still referees to something that has been proven multiple times. It is NOT something that has no proof.

These resolve some of the issues around gravitational lensing and the like, but the fact that we can neither detect their existence or their deaths through hawking radiation places hard upper and lower boundaries on their sizes. So still plenty of mystery!
